{"timestamp": "2025-12-07 04:51:23.336092", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nSummary of network health\n- Status: Major data-plane outage in tenant network 10.0.0.0/24. Hosts cannot reach each other, including peers on the same leaf switch.\n- Control plane: All OVS switches report “is_connected: true” to the SDN controller (20.0.0.100). Management network (20.0.0.0/24) is reachable from switches, though with unusually high RTT.\n\nKey observations and evidence\n1) Host-to-host reachability failure\n- Same-leaf failures:\n  - host_1_2 → host_1_1: Destination Host Unreachable from 10.0.0.2 (100% loss)\n  - host_1_1 → host_1_2: timed out\n  - host_2_1 → host_2_2: Destination Host Unreachable from 10.0.0.9 (100% loss)\n- Cross-leaf failures:\n  - host_2_1 → host_1_1: Destination Host Unreachable (100% loss)\n  - host_1_1 → host_2_1: Destination Host Unreachable (100% loss)\n- Interpretation: ICMP “Destination Host Unreachable” generated by the source host implies ARP resolution failed (no L2 connectivity/flooding/learning).\n\n2) Host configurations are correct\n- Example: host_1_1 has eth0 10.0.0.1/24, host_1_2 has eth0 10.0.0.2/24, host_2_1 has 10.0.0.9/24, host_2_2 has 10.0.0.10/24, with straightforward on-link routes:\n  - 10.0.0.0/24 dev eth0 proto kernel scope link src <host_ip>\n- Thus, IP setup on hosts is not the issue.\n\n3) Switch/controller state and OpenFlow programming\n- OVS bridge status:\n  - leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1 each show a Controller \"tcp:20.0.0.100:6633\" with is_connected: true and fail_mode: secure.\n- Flow tables (OpenFlow 1.3) are sparse and inconsistent with required L2 switching:\n  - leaf_1 example: a rule “in_port=1 actions=output:1” (loop to same port), and a few MAC-specific entries with addresses that do not match attached hosts (e.g., dl_src=e2:cc:de:9a:6b:6e).\n  - leaf_2/spine_1 similar: multiple MAC-specific rules referencing MACs not belonging to the actual hosts (hosts’ MACs include 26:31:41:90:20:f0, 6a:3e:1d:94:9e:d4, 46:ba:cc:96:3a:f5, ae:b8:9c:c7:f9:9b). Some rules even output back to the same port.\n  - There are no general L2 learning/flooding behaviors (no NORMAL action, no appropriate table-miss to controller, no rules to handle ARP/broadcast across host ports).\n- In fail_mode=secure, any traffic not explicitly permitted by the controller is dropped. Given the lack of appropriate flows, ARP requests are not flooded/forwarded and fail.\n\n4) Management plane is reachable but slow\n- Pings from leaf_1/leaf_2/spine_1 to 20.0.0.100 succeed but have high RTT (~586–751 ms). This indicates the controller is reachable and connected, but there may be performance issues or scheduling delays. Regardless, the data-plane failure is due to the lack of correct flows, not loss of connectivity to the controller.\n\n5) Interfaces/links are up\n- All host-facing and inter-switch interfaces report UP/RUNNING. Counters on hosts show significant RX from switches (likely LLDP/topology probes), while minimal TX, which is consistent with switches transmitting management frames but not forwarding host-originated L2 traffic.\n\nDetected anomalies\n- Critical: No L2 connectivity within the tenant VLAN/subnet; ARP resolution fails across both leaves, including within the same leaf.\n- Control-plane programming anomaly: OpenFlow rules are present but incorrect/insufficient. They reference unrelated MACs and contain loopback-to-same-port outputs, with no rules to handle ARP/broadcast or general host-to-host traffic.\n- Secondary: Elevated latency on management pings to the controller.\n\nFault localization\n- Affects all OVS data-plane devices (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1) uniformly for tenant traffic.\n- Hosts and links appear healthy (interfaces up, addressing correct).\n- Controller is reachable and connected to switches.\n- Therefore, the fault is centralized at the controller/SDN application programming the flow tables.\n\nLikely root cause\n- The SDN controller (or its control application/pipeline) is misprogramming or not programming the required L2 forwarding behavior for the tenant network. With fail_mode=secure, absent proper flow entries to flood ARP and forward unicast, all unknown/ARP traffic is dropped, producing the observed “Destination Host Unreachable” symptoms.\n- Evidence: Sparse, MAC-specific rules that do not match the actual hosts; self-loop output rules; no general ARP/broadcast handling; consistent failure across both leaves and the spine despite controller connectivity.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 27815, "output_tokens": 3716, "total_tokens": 31531, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 0}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2560}}}
